[0.009, "o", "\u001b[1;2H\u001b[52X\r\n# This is the main Apache HTTP server configuration file.  It contains the\u001b[3;2H configuration directives that give the server its instructions.\u001b[4;2H See <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/> for detailed information.\r\n# In particular, see \u001b[27X\r\n# <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/directives.html>\u001b[7;2H for a discussion of each configuration directive.  \u001b[8;2H\u001b[54X\n Do \u001b[0;10;1m\u000fNOT\u001b[m\u000f simply read the instructions in here without understanding\u001b[10;2H what they do.  They're here only as hints or reminders.  If you are unsure\u001b[11;2H consult the online docs. You have been warned.  \u001b[12;2H\u001b[48X\n Configuration and logfile names: If the filenames you specify for many\u001b[14;2H of the server's control files begin with \"/\" (or \"drive:/\" for Win32), the\r\n# server will use that explicit path.  If the filenames do *not* begin\u001b[16;2H with \"/\", the value of ServerRoot is prepended -- so \"logs/access_log\"\r\n# with ServerRoot set to \"/usr/local/apache2\" will be interpreted by the\u001b[18;2H server as \"/usr/local/apache2/logs/access_log\", whereas \"/logs/access_log\" \u001b[19;2H will be interpreted as '/logs/access_log'.\u001b[15X\r\n\u001b[45X\u001b[21;2H\u001b[40X\r\n# ServerRoot: The top of the directory tree under which the server's\u001b[23;2H configuration, error, and log files are kept.\u001b[8X\u001b[24;2H\u001b[52X\n Do not add a slash at the end of the directory path.  If you point\r\n# ServerRoot at a non-local disk, be sure to specify a local disk on the\u001b[27;2H Mutex directive, if file-based mutexes are used.  If you wish to share the\u001b[28;2H same ServerRoot for multiple httpd daemons, you will need to change at\u001b[29;2H least PidFile.\u001b[37X\r\n#\u001b[49X\r\n\u001b[96mServerRoot\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[92m\"/etc/httpd\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[25X\r\n\u001b[51X\u001b[33;2H\u001b[44X\n Mutex: Allows you to set the mutex mechanism and mutex file directory\u001b[35;2H for individual mutexes, or change the global defaults\u001b[36;2H\u001b[54X\n Uncomment and change the directory if mutexes are file-based and the default\u001b[38;2H mutex file directory is not on a local disk or is not appropriate for some\u001b[39;2H other reason.\u001b[42X\u001b[40;2H\u001b[58X\n Mutex default:/run/httpd\u001b[37X\r\n\u001b[53X\u001b[43;2H\u001b[62X\n Listen: Allows you to bind Apache to specific IP addresses and/or\u001b[45;2H ports, instead of the default. See also the <VirtualHost>\u001b[46;2H directive.\u001b[37X\u001b[47;2H\u001b[62X\n Change this to Listen on specific IP addresses as shown below to \u001b[49;2H prevent Apache from glomming onto all bound IP addresses.\r\n#\u001b[55X\u001b[51;3Histen 12.34.56.78:80\u001b[39X\r\n\u001b[96mListen\u001b[m\u000f 80\u001b[32X\r\n\u001b[47X\u001b[54;2H\u001b[44X\n Dynamic Shared Object (DSO) Support\u001b[20X\u001b[56;2H\u001b[38X\n To be able to use the functionality of a module which was built as a DSO you\u001b[58;2H have to place corresponding `LoadModule' lines at this location so the\u001b[59;2H directives contained in it are actually available _before_ they are used.\u001b[60;2H Statically compiled modules (those listed by `httpd -l') do not need \r\n# to be loaded here.\u001b[24X\u001b[62;2H\u001b[52X\n Example:\u001b[49X\u001b[64;2H LoadModule foo_module modules/mod_foo.so\r\n#\u001b[45X\u001b[66;224H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f,1            Top\u001b[67;15H\u001b[?25h"]
[3.661, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
