[1.151, "o", "\u001b[?25lD"]
[0.011, "o", "\u001b[1;2H\u001b[59X\u001b[2;3HThis is the main Apache HTTP server configuration file.  It contains the\u001b[3;3Hconfiguration directives that give the server its instructions.\u001b[4;2H See <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/> for detailed information.\u001b[5;2H In particular, see \u001b[6;2H <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/directives.html>\r\n# for a discussion of each configuration directive.\u001b[8;2H\u001b[27X\n \u001b[30m\u001b[103mD\u001b[m\u000fo \u001b[0;10;1m\u000fNOT\u001b[m\u000f simply read the instructions in here without understanding\u001b[10;3Hwhat they do.  They're here only as hints or reminders.  If you are unsure\u001b[11;3Hconsult the online docs. You have been warned.  \u001b[25X\u001b[12;2H\u001b[70X\u001b[13;3HConfiguration and logfile names: If the filenames you specify for many\r\n# of the server's control files begin with \"/\" (or \"drive:/\" for Win32), the\u001b[15;3Hserver will use that explicit path.  If the filenames do *not* begin\r\n# with \"/\", the value of ServerRoot is prepended -- so \"logs/access_log\"\r\n# with ServerRoot set to \"/usr/local/apache2\" will be interpreted by the\u001b[18;3Hserver as \"/usr/local/apache2/logs/access_log\", whereas \"/logs/access_log\" \r\n# will be interpreted as '/logs/access_log'.    \u001b[21;2H\u001b[25X\r\n# ServerRoot: The top of the directory tree under which the server's\r\n# configuration, error, and log files are kept.\u001b[24;2H\u001b[18X\r\n# \u001b[30m\u001b[103mD\u001b[m\u000fo not add a slash at the end of the directory path.  If you point\r\n# ServerRoot at a non-local disk, be sure to specify a local disk on the\u001b[27;3HMutex directive, if file-based mutexes are used.  If you wish to share the\r\n# same ServerRoot for multiple httpd daemons, you will need to change at\r\n# least PidFile.\u001b[30;2H\u001b[45X\r\n\u001b[96mServerRoot\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[92m\"/etc/httpd\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[12X\u001b[33;2H\u001b[14X\n Mutex: Allows you to set the mutex mechanism and mutex file directory\r\n# for individual mutexes, or change the global defaults\u001b[36;2H\u001b[46X\n Uncomment and change the directory if mutexes are file-based and the default\r\n# mutex file directory is not on a local disk or is not appropriate for some\u001b[39;3Hother reason.\u001b[32X\u001b[40;2H\u001b[33X\r\n# Mutex default:/run/httpd\r\n\u001b[26X\n#\u001b[36X\r\n# Listen: Allows you to bind Apache to specific IP addresses and/or\u001b[45;3Hports, instead of the default. See also the <VirtualHost>\r\n# directive.\u001b[16X\r\n#\u001b[33X\r\n# Change this to Listen on specific IP addresses as shown below to \r\n# prevent Apache from glomming onto all bound IP addresses.\u001b[50;2H\u001b[29X\nListen 12.34.56.78:80\u001b[12X\r\n\u001b[96mListen\u001b[m\u000f 80\r\n\u001b[48X\u001b[54;2H\u001b[71X\u001b[55;3H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mD\u001b[m\u000fynamic Shared Object (\u001b[30m\u001b[103mD\u001b[m\u000fSO) Support\u001b[8X\r\n\n# To be able to use the functionality of a module which was built as a \u001b[30m\u001b[103mD\u001b[m\u000fSO you\r\n# have to place corresponding `LoadModule' lines at this location so the\r\n# directives contained in it are actually available _before_ they are used.\r\n# Statically compiled modules (those listed by `httpd -l') do not need\r\n# to be loaded here.\r\n#\u001b[33X\r\n# Example:\u001b[11X\r\n# LoadModule foo_module modules/mod_foo.so\u001b[29X\r\n#\u001b[12X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f9,3            Top\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.345, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000fi"]
[0.008, "o", "\u001b[H \u001b[2;3H'Main' server configuration\u001b[45X\u001b[3;2H\u001b[64X\u001b[4;3HThe directives in this section set up the values used by the 'main'  \u001b[5;3Hserver, which responds to any requests that aren't handled by a\u001b[6;4HVirtualHost> definition.  These values also provide defaults for\u001b[7;3Hany <VirtualHost> containers you may define later in the file.\u001b[9;3HAll of these directives may appear inside <VirtualHost> containers,\u001b[10;3Hin which case these default settings will be overridden for the\u001b[11X\u001b[11;3Hvirtual host being defined.\u001b[21X\r\n\n\u001b[72X\u001b[14;2H\u001b[75X\u001b[15;3HServerAdmin: Your address, where problems with the server should be \u001b[16;3He-mailed.  This address appears on some server-generated pages, such  \u001b[17;3Has error documents.  e.g. admin@your-domain.com\u001b[23X\u001b[18;2H\u001b[76X\r\n\u001b[96mServerAdmin\u001b[m\u000f you@\u001b[96mexample\u001b[m\u000f.com\u001b[17X\u001b[22;9HName gives the name and port that the server uses to identify itself.\u001b[23;3HThis can often be determined automatically, but we recommend you specify\u001b[24;2H it explicitly to prevent problems during startup.\u001b[25;2H\u001b[67X\u001b[26;3HIf your host doesn't have a registered DNS name, enter its IP address here.\u001b[27;2H\u001b[75X\nServerName www.example.com:80\u001b[42X\r\n\u001b[16X\n\n# Deny access to the entirety of your server's filesystem. You must\r\n# explicitly permit access to web content directories in other \u001b[33;2H <\u001b[30m\u001b[103mDi\u001b[m\u000frectory> blocks below.\u001b[34;2H\u001b[70X\r\n\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f<\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f\u001b[30m\u001b[103mDi\u001b[0;10;1m\u000frectory\u001b[m\u000f /\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f>\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[42X\r\n    \u001b[96mAllowOverride\u001b[m\u000f none\r\n    \u001b[96mRequire\u001b[m\u000f all denied\u001b[56X\r\n\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f</\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f\u001b[30m\u001b[103mDi\u001b[0;10;1m\u000frectory>\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[64X\r\n\u001b[15X\u001b[41;3HNote that from this point forward you must specifically allow\r\n# particular features to be enabled - so if something's not working as\u001b[43;2H you might expect, make sure that you have specifically enabled it\u001b[44;3Hbelow.\u001b[59X\u001b[45;2H\u001b[58X\r\n\u001b[12X\u001b[48;3HDocumentRoot: The directory out of which you will serve your\u001b[5X\u001b[49;3Hdocuments. By default, all requests are taken from this directory, but\u001b[50;2H symbolic links and aliases may be used to point to other locations.\u001b[51;2H\u001b[21X\r\n\u001b[96mDocumentRoot\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[92m\"/srv/http\"\r\n\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f<\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f\u001b[30m\u001b[103mDi\u001b[0;10;1m\u000frectory\u001b[m\u000f \"/srv/http\"\u001b[0;10;1m\u000f>\r\n\u001b[m\u000f    #\r\n    # Possible values for the Options directive are \"None\", \"All\",\r\n    # or any combination of:\r\n    #   Indexes Includes FollowSymLinks SymLinksifOwnerMatch ExecCGI MultiViews\r\n    #\u001b[67X\r\n    # Note that \"MultiViews\" must be named *explicitly* --- \"Options All\"  \r\n    # doesn't give it to you.\u001b[41X\r\n    #\u001b[15X\r\n    # The Options directive is both complicated and important.  Please see\r\n    # http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/core.html#options\r\n    # for more information.\u001b[15X\r\n    #\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f236,4          42%\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
